[1mNAME[0m
       [1mfisher-tutorial[0m - A tutorial introduction to Fisherman

[1mDESCRIPTION[0m
       This document tells you how to start using Fisherman key features.

[1mINSTALLING[0m [1mPLUGINS[0m
       Install a plugin.

           fisher install <plugin>

       [4mplugin[24m  can  be  name  registered  in the Fisherman index, a URL to a Git
       repository or a path in the local system. Plugins are collected in a spe-
       cial location inside the Fisherman's configuration directory known as the
:[K

cache.

[1mUPDATE[0m [1mAND[0m [1mUNINSTALL[0m
       Update a plugin.

           fisher update <plugin>

       Uninstall a plugin.

           fisher uninstall <plugin>

[1mLIST[0m [1mAND[0m [1mSEARCH[0m
       The list command displays all the plugins you have installed. The  search
       command queries the index to show what's available to install.

       List installed plugins.
:[K

fisher list
             debug
           * fishtape
           > shellder
           * spin
           @ wipe

       The legend consists of:

       [1m*[0m Indicate the plugin is currently installed
       [1m>[0m Indicate the plugin is a prompt
       [1m@[0m Indicate the plugin is a symbolic link

       Search the index.

:[K

fisher search
             ...
           * debug        Conditional debug logger
             errno        POSIX error code/string translator
           * fishtape     TAP producing test runner
             flash        Flash-inspired, thunder prompt
             fzf          Efficient keybindings for fzf
             get          Press any key to continue
             ...
           > shellder     Powerline prompt optimized for speed
             ...

       Get detailed information about a plugin.

           fisher search shellder
           > shellder by simnalamburt
:[K

Powerline prompt optimized for speed
           github.com/simnalamburt/shellder

       Search plugins using tags.

           fisher search --tag={git,test}
             ...
           * fishtape           TAP producing test runner
             git-branch-name    Get the name of the current Git branch
             git-is-repo        Test if the current directory is a Git repo
             git-is-dirty       Test if there are changes not staged for commit
             git-is-stashed     Test if there are changes in the stash
             ...

[1mPLUMBING[0m
       Fisherman  commands are pipe aware. Plumb one with another to create com-
:[K

plex functionality.

       Update all the plugins in the cache.

           fisher list | fisher update -

       Install all the plugins that are currently disabled.

           fisher list --disabled | fisher install

[1mDOTFILES[0m
       When you install a plugin, Fisherman updates a file known as [4mfishfile[24m  to
       track what plugins are currently enabled.

       To customize its location:

:[K

set -g fisher_file ~/.dotfiles/fishfile

[1mPLUGINS[0m
       Plugins can be utilities, prompts, commands or snippets.

   [1mUTILITIES[0m
       Utilities are plugins that define one or more functions which are mean to
       be used in the CLI directly by the user.

       This  example  walks  you  through  creating  [4mwtc[24m,  a  plugin  based   in
       [4mgithub/ngerakines/commitment[24m random commit message generator.

       o   Create a directory and initialize a Git repository.

           mkdir wtc
           cd wtc
:[K

git init
           git remote add origin https://github.com/<you>/wtc

       o   Add the wtc function.

           function wtc -d "Generate a random commit message"
               switch "$argv"
                   case -h --help
                       printf "Usage: wtc [--help]\n\n"
                       printf "  -h --help  Show usage help\n"
                       return
               end
               curl -s whatthecommit.com/index.txt
           end

       o   Install the plugin.
:[K

fisher install .
           wtc
           (\ /)
           (O.o)
           (> <) Bunny approves these changes.

       o   Commit changes and push to your remote origin when you are done.

           git add --all
           git commit -m "What the commit?"
           git push origin master

       To submit wtc to the official index.

           fisher install submit
:[K

fisher submit

       This  will  create a PR in the Fisherman index repository. Once the PR is
       approved, Fisherman users will be able to install wtc if  they  have  the
       latest index.

           fisher install wtc

       See [1mfisher[0m [1mhelp[0m [1msubmit[0m for more submit options.

       Create a completions directory and add a completions file.

           mkdir completions
           cat > completions/wtc.fish
           complete --command wtc --short h --long help --description "Show usage help"
           ^
:[K

Alternatively, use [1m__fisher_complete[0m to create completions from wtc usage
       output.

           wtc --help | __fisher_complete wtc

       Create a man/man1 directory and add a man(1) page for wtc.

       There are utilities that can help you generate  man  pages  from  various
       text formats. For example, pandoc(1) and ronn(1).

       To create a man page manually.

           mkdir -p man/man1
           cat > man/man1/wtc.1

:[K

.TH man 1 "Today" "1.0" "wtc man page"
            .SH NAME
            wtc \- Generate a random commit message
            .SH SYNOPSIS
            wtc [--help]
            .SH OPTIONS
            -h, --help: Display help information.
            .SH SEE ALSO
            https://github.com/ngerakines/commitment
           ^C

       A plugin can list dependencies to other plugins using a [4mfishfile[24m.

       Create  a new file in the root of your project and add the name or URL of
       your desired dependencies.

:[K

cat > fishfile
           my_plugin
           https://github.com/owner/another_plugin
           ^D

   [1mPROMPTS[0m
       Prompts, also known as themes, are plugins that modify the appearance  of
       the shell prompt.

       Create a [1mfish_prompt[0m function.

           function fish_prompt
               printf "%s (%s) >> " (prompt_pwd) Fisherman
           end
           ~ (Fisherman) >> type here

:[K

To add a right prompt, create a [1mfish_right_prompt[0m function.

           function fish_right_prompt
               printf "%s" (date +%H:%M:%S)
           end

       Save the functions to a directory and install the prompt as a plugin.

           mkdir my_prompt
           cd my_prompt
           functions fish_prompt > fish_prompt.fish
           functions fish_right_prompt > fish_right_prompt.fish
           fisher install .

   [1mCOMMANDS[0m
       Commands  are  plugins  that  extend  the Fisherman CLI adding new [1mfisher[0m
:[K

[1m<commands>[0m.

       Create a function [1mfisher_<command>[0m

           function fisher_time -d "Say hello"
               printf "It's %s\n" (date +%H:%M)
           end

       Test it works

           fisher time
           It's 6:30

       Make it a plugin

           fisher install fisher_time
:[K

This creates a new directory fisher_time in the current working directory
       and installs the plugin.

       The  following  example implements a command to format plugin information
       into columns.

           function fisher_info -d "Display information about plugins"
               switch "$argv"
                   case -h --help
                       printf "Usage: fisher info <name or URL> [...]\n\n"

printf "    -h --help  Show usage help\n"
                       return
               end

               for item in $argv
:[K

fisher search $item --name --info
               end | sed -E 's/;/: /' | column
           end

           fisher install fisher_info

   [1mSNIPPETS[0m
       Snippets are plugins that run code at the start of  the  shell.  Snippets
       must be placed inside a sub directory named conf.d.

       The  following  example  implements the fish_postexec hook to display the
       runtime of the last command in milliseconds.

           mkdir -p runtime/conf.d
           cd runtime
           cat > conf.d/fish_postexec.fish
:[K

function fish_postexec --on-event fish_postexec
               printf "%sms\n" $CMD_DURATION > /dev/stderr
           end
           ^D
           fisher install ./postexec
